<pre class="bz_comment_text" >The situation is getting worse the more I'm looking into it. It turns out that
the /etc/tcsd.conf file MUST be owned by tss:tss mode 600. In this config
paths to kernel files as well as to the system_ps_file are defined:

 root # grep system_ps_file /etc/tcsd.conf
 # Option: system_ps_file
 # system_ps_file = /var/lib/tpm/system.data

This means the unprivileged tss user can not only stage a symlink attack in
/var/lib/tpm, but it can also change the path where the tcsd is trying to
create /var/lib/tpm with mode 0700. Luckily the code isn't `chown()`'ing this
path to the tss user, otherwise we'd have a full tss to root privilege
escalation.

There might be more attack vectors through the config file like information
leaks.

A fix needs to change the mode and ownership of /etc/tcsd.conf to root:tss
0640. There's no need for the tss user to write to this config file.</pre>
